Biodiversity generally refers to the billions of unique living organisms including unicellular bacteria, archaea, and fungi to giant animals such as blue whales, African elephants, and giraffes and plants such as Ficus, Conifers, and Cycades on Earth. These all biological components are in interaction with each, which changes as a result of a change in environmental factors. This defines the diversity among species in the biosphere. All ecosystems such as sea, water, and land where living organisms are found are pivotal for various ecosystem services we humans receive (Haahtela, 2022). Biodiversity is the variety of plants and animals inhabiting an ecosystem. It occurs at three different levels, namely, species diversity, genetic diversity, and ecosystem diversity (Fig. 5.1
). The importance of biodiversity in a particular ecosystem will positively affect the quality of life of other living organisms in the environment and will support the needs that may arise. Biodiversity will be able to offer such advantages by facilitating energy flow and even information transfer, especially material circulation within the ecosystem (Gora et al., 2022; L. Liu, Zhang, et al., 2022). The importance of biodiversity continues to increase from the past to the present. The identification of new species and new highly valuable products is pressing the importance of biodiversity for a sustainable bioeconomy (
