). Throughout history, biodiversity has provided many services that human societies depend on materially, spiritually, culturally, and esthetically (Cafaro, 2022). Biodiversity forms the basis of the functioning of all ecosystems. Similarly, biodiversity has value both on its own and in terms of ecological, genetic, social, economic, scientific, cultural, recreational, and esthetic aspects (providing various ecological services) (Costanza et al., 1997). In addition, biodiversity is important for the maintenance and evolution of life support systems in the biosphere (Linhares et al., 2023; Sobti et al., 2023). As an example of the importance of biodiversity, in an ecosystem where there are many different plant species, plants can gain resistance against invasive organisms that can harm them and can provide more production. For instance, diverse native plant communities tend to be resistant to biological invasion and resilient to a range of abiotic threats meantime providing multiple ecosystem services (Gross et al., 2017). Likewise, the diversity of living organisms in the aquatic ecosystem can provide various ecosystem services including but not limited to, water purification, carbon sequestration, nutrient balance, and maintaining chemical and biological oxygen demand (Scherer-Lorenzen et al., 2022). Biodiversity plays an important role in meeting people’s food, medicine, and other requirements we encounter in every walk of life and thus contributes to various sustainable development goals (SDGs). Biodiversity is especially essential for food security (Zero Hunger SDG 2). The basis of all agricultural products and plant and animal species produced is based on their wild relatives in nature. Today, wild species are used to obtain new agricultural products or to improve existing ones according to the needs of people (Hazarika et al., 2022; Saaondo & Olalekan, 2023). By providing clean air, water, and soil with such advantages where biodiversity exists, a better sustainable environment is provided where various requirements for human life can be met (Brevik et al., 2022). Without biodiversity conservation, achieving SDGs is only wishful thinking. According to biodiversity research, exposure to natural habitats enhances the human microbiota, maintains immunological balance, and guards against allergies and inflammatory illnesses (Haahtela, 2019). The existing order may be disrupted by the reduction or negative impact on biodiversity and threat to some species. Extreme weather events such as heat waves, floods, storms, and tornadoes have quick and substantially visible impacts on biodiversity. However, the results from a great deal of theoretical and empirical studies show that the greatest threat to biodiversity is due to intensified agricultural activities, urban development, and the unparallel use of fossil-based energies. The majority of the losses in biodiversity are due to excessive population growth and urbanization as well as the irregular use of natural resources, pollution, destruction, and climate change (Chapungu et al., 2023; Prakash & Verma, 2022). Natural systems that give humans food, water, and other benefits from nature have undergone tremendous stress due to the fast degradation of ecosystems and biodiversity over the past 50 years (McElwee et al., 2020). Along with the increasing threats to biodiversity, they reported that as a result of the studies conducted between 2006 and 2015, the number of living species under the threat of extinction increased and according to the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment, 60% of the ecosystem was completely deteriorated and irreversibly destroyed (Habibullah et al., 2022). Many strategies are being developed and implemented to protect biodiversity. At the beginning of these, measures such as limiting urbanization and keeping it away from threatened ecosystems reduced the use of chemical materials such as the irregular use of pesticides, especially by farmers, preventing wild hunting and raising awareness among people can be taken (Barral & Guillet, 2023; Mueller et al., 2023; Pour, 2023).
